{
  "texts": [
    "Each level contains a diversified NSW graph built using a sample of nodes from the level below, with the lowest layer sampling from the entire dataset.",
    "Stacked NSW is constructed by assigning each node a maximum level L. Nodes with L>0 are incrementally inserted into the graphs from layer L down to 1.",
    "The maximum level L is:𝐿 = -ln (𝜉) ln (𝑀 ÷ 2) (Eq. 1 [97])where 𝜉 is a uniformly random number between 0 and 1, and 𝑀 is the maximum out-degree in the graphs, controlling the probability distribution of a node's maximum layer.",
    "A high M decreases the number of nodes represented in hierarchical layers as well as the number of layers, while a lower M allocates more nodes to the hierarchical layers, thus generating more hierarchical layers.",
    "During query answering, it starts a greedy search from a fixed entry point at the top layer, descending layer by layer, each time starting from the closest node found in the previous layer, until reaching the bottom layer."
  ]
}